{{about||the Medal of Honor recipient|James Robb Church|the inventor of the snow sampler|James E. Church}}

'''James Church''' is the [[pseudonym]] of the author of five [[detective novel]]s featuring a [[North Korea]]n policeman, "Inspector O".

Church is identified on the back cover of his novels as "a former Western intelligence officer with decades of experience in Asia".<ref name="Slate 2010">{{cite news 
 | last = Bosch | first = Torie | accessdate= 2010-09-07 | date = 2011-09-06
 | title =Why Don't More North Koreans Defect? James Church's Inspector O detective series offers surprising insights.
 | url = http://www.slate.com/id/2262159/  | newspaper =[[Slate (magazine)|Slate]]
}}</ref> He grew up in the [[San Fernando Valley]] in the United States, and was over sixty years old in 2009.<ref name="LAT 2009">{{cite news 
 | last = Demick | first = Barbara | newspaper=[[Los Angeles Times]]
 | title=A novel look at North Korea | accessdate = 2010-09-07 | date = 2009-05-02
 | url=http://articles.latimes.com/2009/may/02/world/fg-korea-detective2
}}</ref>

His "Inspector O" novels have been well-received, being noted by Asia specialists for offering "an unusually nuanced and detailed portrait" of North Korean society.<ref name="Washington Post 2006">{{cite news
 | last = Kessler | first=Glenn l | accessdate = 2010-09-07 | date = 2006-12-27
 | title =The Book on North Korea: Thriller Provides Rare Glimpse of Closed Nation |newspaper=[[Washington Post]]
 | url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/wp-dyn/content/article/2006/12/26/AR2006122600798.htm
}}</ref> A [[Korea Society]] panel praised the first book in the series for its realism and its ability to convey "the suffocating atmosphere of a [[totalitarian]] state".<ref>{{cite web
 |title=A Corpse in the Koryo: A North Korean Murder Mystery 
 |url=http://www.koreasociety.org/culture_policy_society/culture_policy_society/a_corpse_in_the_koryo_a_north_korean_murder_mystery.html 
 |publisher=[[Korea Society]] 
 |accessdate=2010-09-07 
 |date=2007-05-08 
 |deadurl=yes 
 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100802141418/http://www.koreasociety.org/culture_policy_society/culture_policy_society/a_corpse_in_the_koryo_a_north_korean_murder_mystery.html 
 |archivedate=August 2, 2010 
}}</ref> ''[[The Independent]]''<ref name="Independent 2007">{{cite news
 | last = Cornwell | first = Rupert  | accessdate = 2010-09-07 | date= 2007-02-17
 | title=State of suspense: Unlocking the enigma of North Korea | newspaper = [[The Independent]] 
 | url=https://www.independent.co.uk/news/world/asia/state-of-suspense-unlocking-the-enigma-of-north-korea-436666.html
}}</ref> and the ''[[Washington Post]]'' compared the protagonist to [[Arkady Renko]], the [[Soviet Union|Soviet]] chief inspector in [[Martin Cruz Smith]]'s ''[[Gorky Park (novel)|Gorky Park]]'', for providing "a vivid window into a mysterious country".<ref name="Washington Post 2006" />

