{{Citation style|section|date=September 2009}}
'''Jean Lafleur''' is a [[Canadians|Canadian]] businessman famous for his role in the [[Liberal Party of Canada]] [[sponsorship scandal]].
==Role in Sponsorship scandal== On April 27, 2007, Lafleur returned to Canada from a two-year stay in [[Belize]], where he was reported to have lived in an exclusive villa and enjoyed fine wines. Lafleur pleaded guilty to 28 fraud charges for his role in the scandal.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.theglobeandmail.com/servlet/story/RTGAM.20070427.wlafleur0427/BNStory/National/home|first=Tu Thanh|last=Ha|title=Lafleur pleads guilty to 28 fraud charges|publisher=The Globe and Mail|date=27 April 2007|accessdate=2007-04-27}}{{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20070429040401/https://www.theglobeandmail.com/servlet/story/RTGAM.20070427.wlafleur0427/BNStory/National/home|date=29 April 2007}}</ref> He gave 76 false invoices to [[Charles Guite]], the civil servant responsible for the sponsorship program in Public Works Department of the federal government in the 1990s.<ref name="lfpress">[http://www.lfpress.ca/newsstand/News/National/2007/06/28/4296708-sun.html lfpress.ca]</ref>
Counting time served, Lafleur was given a sentence of 42 months in prison,<ref name="lfpress"/> and ordered to pay back CDN $1.6 million to the federal government. His sentence was the highest handed out in the scandal, as he showed no remorse or co-operation in the investigation and trial.<ref name="lfpress"/> The [[crown prosecutor]] had sought a sentence of five years.<ref name="cbc">[http://www.cbc.ca/canada/ottawa/story/2007/06/27/lafleur-sponsorhip.html?ref=rss cbc.ca]</ref>
