{{Infobox criminal | name = John Charles Gilkey | image = | image_size = | alt = | caption = | birth_name = | birth_date = {{Birth year and age|1968}} | birth_place = [[Modesto, California]], [[United States]] | death_date = <!-- {{Death date and age|YYYY|MM|DD|YYYY|MM|DD}} (death date then birth date) --> | death_place = | death_cause = | resting_place = | residence = | nationality = [[United States|American]] | other_names = | occupation = | known_for = | height = | weight = | predecessor = | successor = | religion = | criminal_charge = [[Document theft|Book and document theft]], [[check fraud]] | penalty = | conviction_status = | spouse = <!--Do not include spouse unless notable or they are relevant to the crime.--> | children = <!--Do not include children unless notable or they are relevant to the crime.--> | parents = <!--Do not include parents unless notable or they are relevant to the crime.--> | allegiance = <!-- [[Lucchese crime family]] --> | motive = | conviction = | reward_amount = | capture_status = | wanted_by = | partners = | wanted_since = | time_at_large = | escaped = | escape_end = | comments = | victims = | date = | time = | beginyear = | endyear = | country = | states = | locations = | targets = | fatalities = | injuries = | weapons = | apprehended = | imprisoned = | footnotes = }} '''John Charles Gilkey''' (born 1968)<ref>{{cite web|last1=Ciuraru|first1=Carmela|title='The Man Who Loved Books Too Much' by Allison Hoover Bartlett|url=http://articles.latimes.com/2009/nov/05/entertainment/et-book5|website=LA Times|date=November 5, 2009|accessdate=June 6, 2017}}</ref> is a prolific [[Document theft|book and document thief]] who has stolen approximately US$200,000 worth of rare books and manuscripts.<ref>{{cite web|last=Ann |first=Mary |url=http://seattletimes.nwsource.com/html/books/2013047986_litlife04.html |title=Thief stole rare books for love, says author |publisher=Seattle Times |date=2010-10-03 |accessdate=2012-01-14}}</ref> Gilkey used Modern Library's List of 100 Best Novels<ref>[http://www.modernlibrary.com/top-100/100-best-novels/ Modern Library's List of 100 Best Novels]</ref> as a guide to what items he would steal.<ref>{{cite journal|last=Berkes|first=Howard|title=Literary Larceny: A Book Thief Meets His Match|journal=NPR|date=January 2010}}</ref> His motives for the thefts were personal: he saw an expansive library as a sign of being upper-class.<ref>{{harvnb|Bartlett|2009|p=101}}</ref>
Gilkey used bad checks and stolen credit card numbers gained through his employment at [[Saks Fifth Avenue]] in San Francisco.<ref name=Berkes>{{cite web|last=Berkes|first=Howard|title=Literary Larceny: A Book Thief Meets His Match|url=http://www.wbur.org/npr/121489286/literary-larceny-a-book-thief-meets-his-match|work=All Things Considered|publisher=NPR.org|accessdate=10 April 2011|date=January 2010}}</ref> He did not consider that he stole books; instead he would talk about "doing business" with the dealers from whom he stole items. Allison Hoover Bartlett, who wrote ''The Man Who Loved Books Too Much'' chronicling Gilkey's thefts and methods, stated that he felt he deserved the books. She also noted that Gilkey would tell her the details of a theft after the statute of limitations on that crime had expired.<ref>{{harvnb|Bartlett|2009|p=243}}</ref>
After a [[sting operation]] in 2003 orchestrated by [[Ken Sanders (book dealer)|Ken Sanders]], a rare book dealer in Salt Lake City,<ref>{{cite news|publisher=San Jose Mercury News (California)|date=February 7, 2003 |title=Book-theft suspect caught with the goods |author=John Woolfolk |quote=He was a thief who allegedly used a stolen credit card number to buy the original bestseller and reserve a room at the hotel where he planned to pick it up, police say. Now investigators say they have connected the man, John Charles Gilkey, to at least one other similar rare-book theft in the Bay Area and are looking into whether he is linked to others over the last two years worth $50,000... Gilkey, who was on probation out of Los Angeles for writing bad checks, told police he was unemployed and living on the streets of San Francisco. So officers were surprised when he promptly posted $15,000 bail.}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |last=Redfearn |first=Dixie |url=http://www.theunion.com/article/20070519/NEWS/105190193 |title=Meet 'Book Cop' at Gold Rush fair |publisher=The Union |date=2007-05-19 |accessdate=2012-01-14 |deadurl=yes |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110914093148/http://www.theunion.com/article/20070519/NEWS/105190193 |archivedate=2011-09-14 |df= }}</ref> Gilkey served 18 months in [[San Quentin]] beginning the following year.<ref name=Berkes/>
He was arrested again on December 15, 2010, in San Francisco for stealing two antique maps.<ref>{{cite web|last=Lieberman|first=Michael|title=The Man Who Loved Books Too Much is back on the loose|url=http://blog.seattlepi.com/bookpatrol/2010/12/15/the-man-who-loved-books-too-much-is-back-on-the-loose/|work=Book Patrol|publisher=Seattle Pi|accessdate=10 April 2011 |date=December 15, 2010}}</ref>
Gilkey was the subject of an episode of the podcast ''[[Criminal (podcast)|Criminal]]''.<ref>{{cite episode| title =Ex-libris | episodelink = | series =Criminal | serieslink = | airdate =26 June 2015 | season = | number =22 }}</ref>
