[[Image:Striking workers coburn kleinfeldt eye clinic Dearborn Michigan.JPG|thumb|250px|right|Picketing workers, [[Dearborn, Michigan]]]]
'''Labor unrest''' is [[strike action]] or [[industrial action]] undertaken by [[labor union]]s, especially where [[:Category:Labor disputes|labor disputes]] become [[Violence in industrial disputes|violent]]. Such a conception of labor action was common in the [[United States]] in the 19th century,<ref>{{cite book|last=Arnesen|first=Eric|title=Encyclopedia of United States Labor and Working-class History|year=2007|publisher=CRC Press|pages=123|url=https://books.google.com/?id=zEWsZ81Bd3YC&pg=PA123&dq=labor+dispute+american+history#v=onepage&q=labor%20dispute%20american%20history&f=false|isbn=9780415968263}}</ref> most prominently among [[mining|mining interests]] in the [[American West]], and remained common in the 20th century among [[Communism|communist]] states, such as the [[Soviet Union]] and [[People's Republic of China]].{{Citation needed|date=February 2007}}

